  "text": "Watch Event Delivery Path in Kubernetes\n\nThe path of a watch event from etcd to a client application involves multiple layers:\n\n1. ETCD SOURCE LAYER (etcd-io/etcd):\n   - server/mvcc/watcher.go: Contains the WatchStream interface and watchStream struct that represents a stream of watch responses from the MVCC store. The watchStream type holds a collection of watchers and a shared channel for sending watch events.\n   - server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/watch.go: Defines the serverWatchStream struct (line 121) which handles the server-side gRPC watch stream. It manages the communication between the gRPC stream and the underlying MVCC WatchStream, handling both incoming watch create/cancel requests (via recvLoop) and outgoing watch events (via sendLoop).\n\n2. KUBERNETES APISERVER CACHE LAYER (kubernetes/kubernetes):\n   - staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/cacher.go: The Cacher struct (line 250) is the core caching component that implements the storage.Interface. It maintains a reflector for doing ListAndWatch operations to populate its cache, and manages a watchCache for efficient watch event distribution.\n   - staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/watch_cache.go: The watchCache struct (line 91) implements a sliding window of recently observed objects from a watch. It maintains a bounded cache of events and serves as the internal data store for the Cacher.\n   - staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/cacher/cache_watcher.go: The cacheWatcher struct (line 53) implements the watch.Interface and is created for each client watch request. It receives events from the watchCache through an input channel and filters/forwards them to the client.\n\n3. CLIENT-SIDE REFLECTOR (kubernetes/client-go):\n   - tools/cache/reflector.go: The Reflector struct (line 59) on the client side performs ListAndWatch operations against the apiserver. It receives watch events from the watch response stream and stores them in a local Store (typically a thread-safe cache). The Reflector is responsible for handling watch disconnections, resync operations, and maintaining the local cache in sync with the server.\n\nThe complete flow is:\n1. Client initiates a watch via the apiserver\n2. Apiserver's Cacher.Watch() creates a cacheWatcher\n3. The Cacher's reflector (client-go Reflector) watches etcd and receives events through serverWatchStream\n4. The Cacher distributes events to all cacheWatchers via watchCache\n5. The cacheWatcher receives filtered events and sends them to the client\n6. Meanwhile, other clients use client-go's Reflector to directly watch the apiserver and receive these watch events in their local stores"
}

